# Async Patterns

Use async/await consistently. Handle errors at appropriate levels. Use Promise utilities for concurrent operations and timeouts.

---

## Triggers

**APPLY WHEN:** Writing async code, handling promises, implementing retries or timeouts.
**SKIP WHEN:** Synchronous-only code or simple one-off fetches.

---

## Core Directive

**Use async/await consistently** - Avoid mixing callbacks and promises. Handle errors at boundaries, not at every level.

---

## Try/Catch for Async/Await

**Wrap await calls in try/catch; let errors propagate to boundaries:**

```typescript
// Good: Try/catch at appropriate level
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`);
  }
  const data: unknown = await response.json();
  return validateUser(data);
}

// Good: Higher-level handler
async function loadUserProfile(userId: string) {
  try {
    const user = await fetchUser(userId);
    setUser(user);
  } catch (error) {
    showErrorToast(error instanceof Error ? error.message : "Failed to load");
  }
}

// Bad: Catching at every level
async function badFetch() {
  try {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    try {
      const data = await res.json();
      try {
        return process(data);
      } catch (e) { /* redundant */ }
    } catch (e) { /* redundant */ }
  } catch (e) { /* redundant */ }
}
```

